<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="580" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1777,2018]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,151,789]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="580" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1778,1802]" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">Remarks.</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[445,559,1778,1801]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Paropesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[445,559,1778,1801]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">Paropesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[705,832,1778,1801]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Parerigone" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[705,832,1778,1801]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">Parerigone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the external characters. It is distinguished from the latter by the bare eye and 
<number box="[439,481,1814,1838]" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
rows of black hairs on the occiput. 
<taxonomicName box="[879,993,1814,1837]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Paropesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[879,993,1814,1837]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">Paropesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks yellowish hairs on the thorax and abdomen, is missing the ventral seta on the mid tibia in the male, and has only three pairs of marginal scutellar setae, whereas these characters are variable among species of 
<taxonomicName box="[854,980,1886,1909]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Parerigone" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[854,980,1886,1909]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">Parerigone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the male terminalia the fundamental structure is the same in both genera: 
<number box="[575,588,1921,1946]" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" value="6.0">6</number>
th tergite entire and free from syntergosternite 
<number box="[1124,1138,1922,1946]" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" value="7.0">7</number>
+ 
<number box="[1155,1168,1922,1946]" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" value="8.0">8</number>
(
<figureCitation box="[1185,1280,1921,1946]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1623,1646]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,277,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,265,1603]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 12. Male terminalia of Paropesia discalis sp. nov. 6. Epandrium, cerci and surstylus in dorsal view. 7. Same in lateral view. 8. Hypandrium, pregonite, postgonite and phallus in lateral view. 9. Apex of phallus in posterior view. 10. Ejaculatory apodeme in dorsal view. 11. 5 th sternite in ventral view. 12. 6 th tergite and syntergosternite 7 + 8 in lateral view. Scale for Figs. 6 – 10: 0.1 mm, for Figs. 11, 12: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230554/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">Figs. 12</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1294,1325,1921,1946]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 – 26" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1495,1518]" captionTargetBox="[173,1417,401,1472]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1424,391,1481]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 24 – 26. Male terminalia of Paropesia grisea sp. nov. 24. 5 th sternite in ventral view. 25. 6 th tergite, syntergosternite 7 + 8 and 5 th sternite in lateral view. 26. Epandrium, cerci and surstylus in ventral view. Scale for Figs. 24, 25: 0.2 mm, for Fig. 26: 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230557/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">25</figureCitation>
), rod-like pregonite and postgonite closely associated with each other, and phallus elongate with apex expanded (
<figureCitation box="[1309,1389,1957,1982]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1623,1646]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,277,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,265,1603]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 12. Male terminalia of Paropesia discalis sp. nov. 6. Epandrium, cerci and surstylus in dorsal view. 7. Same in lateral view. 8. Hypandrium, pregonite, postgonite and phallus in lateral view. 9. Apex of phallus in posterior view. 10. Ejaculatory apodeme in dorsal view. 11. 5 th sternite in ventral view. 12. 6 th tergite and syntergosternite 7 + 8 in lateral view. Scale for Figs. 6 – 10: 0.1 mm, for Figs. 11, 12: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230554/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1401,1431,1958,1982]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 23" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[163,1428,322,1800]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,303,1801]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 23. Male terminalia of Paropesia grisea sp. nov. 19. Epandrium, cerci and surstylus in dorsal view. 20. Same in lateral view. 21. Hypandrium, pregonite, postgonite and phallus in lateral view. 22. Apex of phallus in dorsal view. 23. Ejaculatory apodeme in dorsal view. Scale: 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230556/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">21</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,183,1994,2018]" captionStart="FIGURES 27 – 32" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1453,1476]" captionTargetBox="[168,1420,203,1419]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,195,1430]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 27 – 32. Male terminalia of Paropesia tessellata sp. nov. 27. Epandrium, cerci and surstylus in lateral view. 28. Same in dorsal view. 29. Hypandrium, pregonite, postgonite and phallus in lateral view. 30. Apex of phallus in posterior view. 31. Ejaculatory apodeme in dorsal view. 32. 5 th sternite in ventral view. Scale for Figs. 27 – 31: 0.1 mm, for Fig. 32: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230558/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">
<number box="[151,183,1994,2018]" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" value="29.0">29</number>
</figureCitation>
). However, in 
<taxonomicName box="[349,463,1994,2017]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Paropesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[349,463,1994,2017]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">Paropesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the median cleft of the male 
<number box="[798,811,1993,2018]" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" value="5.0">5</number>
th abdominal sternite is not wide (
<figureCitation box="[1200,1293,1993,2018]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1623,1646]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,277,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,265,1603]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 12. Male terminalia of Paropesia discalis sp. nov. 6. Epandrium, cerci and surstylus in dorsal view. 7. Same in lateral view. 8. Hypandrium, pregonite, postgonite and phallus in lateral view. 9. Apex of phallus in posterior view. 10. Ejaculatory apodeme in dorsal view. 11. 5 th sternite in ventral view. 12. 6 th tergite and syntergosternite 7 + 8 in lateral view. Scale for Figs. 6 – 10: 0.1 mm, for Figs. 11, 12: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230554/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">Figs. 11</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1306,1336,1994,2018]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 – 26" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1495,1518]" captionTargetBox="[173,1417,401,1472]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[164,1424,391,1481]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 24 – 26. Male terminalia of Paropesia grisea sp. nov. 24. 5 th sternite in ventral view. 25. 6 th tergite, syntergosternite 7 + 8 and 5 th sternite in lateral view. 26. Epandrium, cerci and surstylus in ventral view. Scale for Figs. 24, 25: 0.2 mm, for Fig. 26: 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230557/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">24</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1349,1380,1994,2018]" captionStart="FIGURES 27 – 32" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1453,1476]" captionTargetBox="[168,1420,203,1419]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,195,1430]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 27 – 32. Male terminalia of Paropesia tessellata sp. nov. 27. Epandrium, cerci and surstylus in lateral view. 28. Same in dorsal view. 29. Hypandrium, pregonite, postgonite and phallus in lateral view. 30. Apex of phallus in posterior view. 31. Ejaculatory apodeme in dorsal view. 32. 5 th sternite in ventral view. Scale for Figs. 27 – 31: 0.1 mm, for Fig. 32: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230558/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="579">
<number box="[1349,1380,1994,2018]" pageId="3" pageNumber="579" value="32.0">32</number>
</figureCitation>
), the cerci are broadly separated on posterior half, and the phallus is cylindrical and more broadly sclerotized, whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,278,189,212]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Parerigone" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,278,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Parerigone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the median cleft of 
<number box="[501,513,188,213]" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" value="5.0">5</number>
th sternite is very wide, the cerci are at most only a little separated, and the phallus is broadly membranous. In the female terminalia 
<taxonomicName box="[704,818,224,247]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Paropesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[704,818,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Paropesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is different from 
<taxonomicName box="[1016,1142,224,247]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Parerigone" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1016,1142,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Parerigone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a very long and invaginated 
<number box="[290,303,260,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" value="6.0">6</number>
th sternite, very stout and posteriorly flattened 
<number box="[841,854,260,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" value="7.0">7</number>
th sternite, well developed epiproct, and a balloonshaped or triangularly expanded membranous lobe with microvilli behind 
<number box="[986,999,295,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" value="7.0">7</number>
th tergite (
<figureCitation box="[1116,1337,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 18. 13 – 15" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[162,1430,209,1766]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,195,1766]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 18. 13 – 15. Female terminalia of Paropesia discalis sp. nov. 13. Lateral view. 14. Dorsal view. 15. Ventral view (hairs omitted). 16 – 18. Female terminalia of P. gr i s e a sp. nov. 16. Lateral view. 17. Dorsal view (hairs omitted). 18. Ventral view (hairs omitted). Scale: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230555/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Figs. 13, 14, 16, 17</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1349,1424,296,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 33 – 35" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1963,1986]" captionTargetBox="[158,1422,958,1938]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,949,1942]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 33 – 35. Female terminalia of Paropesia tessellata sp. nov. 33. Lateral view. 34. Dorsal view. 35. Ventral view (hairs omitted). Scale: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230559/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">33, 34</figureCitation>
). The function of this last structure is unknown, but it is a peculiar feature of the known species of this genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">
<taxonomicName box="[199,313,368,391]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Paropesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,313,368,391]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Paropesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also resembles another Oriental parerigonine genus, 
<taxonomicName authority="Mesnil" authorityName="Mesnil" box="[936,1191,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Zambesomima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[936,1099,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Zambesomima</emphasis>
Mesnil
</taxonomicName>
, in its bare eye, fine ocellar setae and female piercing ovipositor (
<number box="[654,667,404,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" value="8.0">8</number>
th abdominal sternite), but differs from the latter in its black hairs on the occiput (only whitish hairs in 
<taxonomicName box="[529,692,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Zambesomima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[529,692,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Zambesomima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), three pairs of scutellar setae (of which apical pair are strong and crossed; 
<number box="[252,266,476,500]" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" value="4.0">4</number>
pairs and apical setae absent in 
<taxonomicName box="[640,803,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Zambesomima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[640,803,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Zambesomima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and male always lacking ventral seta on the mid tibia (male with ventral seta in 
<taxonomicName box="[441,605,512,536]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Zambesomima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[441,605,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Zambesomima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as in female of 
<taxonomicName box="[790,904,512,535]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Paropesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[790,904,512,535]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Paropesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The male and female terminalia are similar in both genera: the hypandrium flattened, pregonite and postgonite rod-like and closely associated; phallus elongate. As mentioned above, 
<taxonomicName box="[404,518,584,607]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Paropesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[404,518,584,607]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Paropesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[535,661,584,607]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Parerigone" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[535,661,584,607]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Parerigone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[722,886,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Zambesomima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[722,886,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Zambesomima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resemble one another in the external structures including the male and female terminalia. They may be united in a monophyletic group in the Parerigonini as sharing a synapomorphic character state of a long rod-like pregonite closely associated with the postgonite. The Neotropical genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Townsend" authorityName="Townsend" box="[370,649,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Neobrachelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[370,523,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Neobrachelia</emphasis>
Townsend
</taxonomicName>
appears to possess this character state (
<bibRefCitation author="Tschorsnig" box="[1119,1423,692,717]" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" refString="Tschorsnig, H. - P. (1985) Taxonomie forstlich wichtiger Parasiten: Untersuchungen zur Structur des mannlichen Postabdomens der Raupenfliegen (Diptera, Tachinidae). Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde, Serie A (383), 1 - 137." type="journal article" year="1985">
Tschorsnig 
<number box="[1254,1314,692,717]" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" value="1985.0">1985</number>
: fig. 
<number box="[1378,1423,692,716]" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" value="144.0">144</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), whereas the Australasian genera of Parerigonini, such as 
<taxonomicName authority="Curran" authorityName="Curran" box="[828,1101,728,752]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Australotachina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[828,1009,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Australotachina</emphasis>
Curran
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Baranov" authorityName="Baranov" box="[1116,1327,728,752]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Leverella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1116,1221,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Leverella</emphasis>
Baranov
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Curran" authorityName="Curran" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Zita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="580" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1391,1436,728,751]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="580">Zita</emphasis>
Curran
</taxonomicName>
, do not.
</paragraph>
